{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538491","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538491"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:28:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:28:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16192"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16192"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.44,0.17,0.25,0.08,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8883"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109629"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8883","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8883"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16192"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92020"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"297"},{"type":"tags","id":"1465"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"2888"},{"type":"tags","id":"4087"},{"type":"tags","id":"4380"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21148"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41044"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43618"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109629","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109629"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic at 22 weeks gestation for routine antenatal care. She reports intermittent vaginal spotting earlier in the pregnancy. She has not had any bleeding at all in the last week. She has no abdominal pain or uterine contractions. This is her second pregnancy with no complications in her first pregnancy. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy vitamins. Her cervical screening test was due six months ago but was not performed. She has had her 20 week morphology ultrasound scan which was normal and placenta was anterior and clear. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The uterus is soft and non-tender, consistent with dates. Doppler ultrasound confirms a fetal heart rate of 142/min. Speculum examination reveals a 2 cm reddish polyp protruding from the external cervical os with contact bleeding. The surrounding cervix appears normal. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Referral to colposcopy clinic","Urgent obstetric review","Expectant management until delivery","Immediate polypectomy in clinic","Diathermy of cervical polyp in clinic"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with antepartum haemorrhage due to a cervical polyp, which is a common benign cause of bleeding in pregnancy. The management approach needs to balance investigating the cause of bleeding while ensuring safety during pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral to colposcopy clinic\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. This allows for expert assessment of the polyp and surrounding cervix in a controlled setting with appropriate equipment. The colposcopist can then make an informed decision about whether removal is necessary during pregnancy and whether the polyp is likely benign of if there is any concern for cervical neoplasia or malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent obstetric review\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary at this stage as the patient is haemodynamically stable with a clear source of bleeding identified. She has also not had any recent bleeding in the last week. The polyp can be managed in the outpatient setting through the colposcopy service. If she has any further fresh bleeding however she should present for obstetric review as it will be difficult to differentiate whether bleeding is due to the polyp or another issue in the pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExpectant management until delivery\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate at this stage as further assessment of the polyp is needed to enable shared decision making with the mother about ongoing management, including the option of polypectomy. Additionally any further bleeding that may occur from the polyp during pregnancy may cause anxiety for the parents and could mask other causes of antepartum haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate polypectomy in clinic\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as it may cause excessive bleeding and should be performed in a setting with appropriate equipment and expertise, particularly during pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiathermy of cervical polyp\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate in pregnancy due to the risk of cervical trauma and bleeding. Any intervention should be performed in a controlled setting by an experienced colposcopist.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cervical polyps can be a benign cause of antepartum haemorrhage that can be safely managed with colposcopy review.","Colposcopy assessment allows for safe evaluation and management of cervical lesions during pregnancy."],"references":["Perkins RB, Guido RS, Castle PE, Chelmow D, Einstein MH, Garcia F, Huh WK, Kim JJ, Moscicki AB, Nayar R, Saraiya M, Sawaya GF, Wentzensen N, Schiffman M; 2019 ASCCP Risk-Based Management Consensus Guidelines Committee. 2019 ASCCP Risk-Based Management Consensus Guidelines for Abnormal Cervical Cancer Screening Tests and Cancer Precursors. J Low Genit Tract Dis. 2020 Apr;24(2):102-131. doi: 10.1097/LGT.0000000000000525. Erratum in: J Low Genit Tract Dis. 2020 Oct;24(4):427. doi: 10.1097/LGT.0000000000000563. PMID: 32243307; PMCID: PMC7147428.","Wang M, Ye M, Shen N, Pan W, et al. Management of pregnant women with endocervical and decidual polyps: A systematic review and meta-analysis. Archives of Gynecology and Obstetrics. 2025. Available at: https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s00404-025-08056-w#citeas"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92020"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16192"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92020","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92020"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-23T15:27:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-23T15:28:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8883"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109629"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","